Project: E-Wallet (PWA/Offline-Supported Mobile Wallet Application)
Role: Senior Software Architect & Flutter Developer
1. Core Technologies and Standards
Framework: Flutter (Material 3 design standards, minimalist interface).

Language: Dart (Null safety MUST STRICTLY be enabled).

Type safety is essential. The dynamic type CANNOT be used.

Class and variable naming must be descriptive and self-explanatory.

Backend & Database: Supabase Flutter SDK (Auth, PostgreSQL database).

State Management: Riverpod (flutter_riverpod or hooks_riverpod).

Routing: GoRouter (For page navigation and transitions).

Offline Storage (Offline First): Isar Database (For offline functionality).

Push Notifications: Firebase Cloud Messaging (FCM).

Automation: Supabase pg_cron (For automatic subscription deductions).

Data Visualization: fl_chart (Pie and bar charts).

2. Category-Based Directory Structure (Feature-First Clean Architecture)
The project must strictly follow a "Feature-First" and organized structure. All code under the lib/ directory must be separated using the following logic:

lib/core/: The heart of the application. Foundational structures used by all modules.

/theme (Colors, typography)

/network (Supabase, Isar connection configurations)

/constants (Constant values, API keys)

/utils (Formatters, helper functions)

/error (Custom error classes)

lib/shared/: Common UI components used across multiple screens.

/widgets (CustomButton, CustomTextField, etc.)

lib/features/: The core of the business logic. Each feature must be isolated within its own folder.

Example: /auth, /budget, /subscriptions, /goals

The internal structure of each feature MUST BE CATEGORIZED as follows:

presentation/: Screens and widgets specific to that feature.

domain/: Data models (Entities) and business rules (Use cases).

data/: Data sources (Isar Local, Supabase Remote) and Repository classes.

providers/: Riverpod State Notifiers specific to that feature.

3. Development Rules and Coding Style
Separation of UI and Business Logic: Heavy business logic cannot be written inside Screen and Widget files. The UI is strictly for displaying data; operations and state modifications must be handled within the Riverpod classes in the providers/ directory.

Error Handling: - Deeply nested if-else blocks are FORBIDDEN. "Guard Clause" and "Early Return" patterns must be utilized.

try/catch blocks must strictly be used in all API or database operations.

Performance: The const keyword MUST strictly be used EVERYWHERE possible (widgets, paddings, texts) to prevent Flutter from unnecessarily redrawing (rebuilding) the screen.